    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a9b3f838_f181cb54",
        "filename": "org.eclipse.jgit/src/org/eclipse/jgit/lib/RefWriter.java",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 45,
      "author": {
        "id": 1022030
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-20T21:39:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e I was talking about the performance of the reads that would happen after `RefWriter` committing the packed-refs (previously all writes were sorted).\n\nYou could keep the requirement that `this.refs` be sorted or you could relax it and still help future debug. Depending on which you choose, in `writePackedRefs()`, if `SORTED` isn\u0027t in the traits, either throw an exception or log a debug-level warning message.",
      "parentUuid": "7a7dc202_6336e032",
      "revId": "d32f41eb16c67ed51b2a9e72107e607263ea2e7e",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ebff1eb9_3615d975",
        "filename": "org.eclipse.jgit/src/org/eclipse/jgit/lib/RefWriter.java",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 45,
      "author": {
        "id": 1038403
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-20T21:46:07Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I believe that our objective should be to write as many traits as jgit supports to ensure good performance. i.e. I see no reason to support not sorting currently, and soon in follow on changes, not peeling (or maybe that should even come in this change). In other words, the new APIs should do the right thing. The only reason to not do those in the old APIs is to avoid regressions from users of those APIs. In my opinion, specifying traits in the new constructors should not be a mechanism to add traits to the file, but rather a mechanism to tell this class what traits the refs already have so that this class can add them without computing them.",
      "parentUuid": "a9b3f838_f181cb54",
      "revId": "d32f41eb16c67ed51b2a9e72107e607263ea2e7e",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "6cb6ffde_c508fbab",
        "filename": "org.eclipse.jgit/src/org/eclipse/jgit/lib/RefWriter.java",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 45,
      "author": {
        "id": 1022030
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-20T21:49:41Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e rather a mechanism to tell this class what traits the refs already have so that this class can add them without computing them.\n\nThat\u0027s exactly how it works in the latest patchset (including not peeling). The question was if we think it\u0027s \"wrong\" to not sort and use RefWriter. Sounds like you think no (i.e. allow it and don\u0027t log anything).",
      "parentUuid": "ebff1eb9_3615d975",
      "revId": "d32f41eb16c67ed51b2a9e72107e607263ea2e7e",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "de4ba644_034d45bc",
        "filename": "org.eclipse.jgit/src/org/eclipse/jgit/lib/RefWriter.java",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 45,
      "author": {
        "id": 1038403
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-20T21:53:32Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Well that part is true, but that missed my point about \"our objective should be to write as many traits as jgit supports to ensure good performance\". Since we jgit currently knows how to sort, it ensure that refs are always sorted. That means sorting refs when the trait is not passed in so that it can safely add it. In a follow on change (or perhaps in this one if we don\u0027t want to change future behavior of the new methods), the new methods should also add peeled and fully-peeled whether they are passe in or not (computing them if not passed in).",
      "parentUuid": "6cb6ffde_c508fbab",
      "revId": "d32f41eb16c67ed51b2a9e72107e607263ea2e7e",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5509d9d6_9e9ed38a",
        "filename": "org.eclipse.jgit/src/org/eclipse/jgit/lib/RefWriter.java",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 45,
      "author": {
        "id": 1022030
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-20T22:24:12Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Ah ok, I did read that, but I thought it meant something different based on how your paragraph ended 🙂\n\nWhile I agree with your high-level goal, this is an abstract class and I\u0027m not sure we can assume all reader/writer implementations have the same performance tradeoffs (though they all seem to be some kind of packed-refs file, so they probably do?).\n\nI\u0027d rather let callers opt-in to that behavior with helper methods. You could do that a few different ways, like adding per-trait helpers (e.g. `.sort()` that sorts the refs and adds `SORTED`) or an overall (static) helper that does some kind of \"apply all missing traits\" logic (e.g. `static createAndApplyMissingTraits(refs, existingTraits)` or `.applyMissingTraits()`).\n\nThat said... if you feel confident that either the writer has to do this work once or readers have to do it N\u003e\u003d1 times and that\u0027s true for any writers/readers, then I would be inclined to make writing an optimized file as \"default\" as possible. If we want to keep the flexibility for some implementation with special behavior, then maybe we add a reverse switch `.doNotApplyMissingTraits()` and we defer any optimizations until we\u0027re in `writePackedRefs()`?",
      "parentUuid": "de4ba644_034d45bc",
      "revId": "d32f41eb16c67ed51b2a9e72107e607263ea2e7e",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    },
    {
